I love you!  But I do take issue with the fact that you say we are going to come into our dream bodies. As someone who works with people with eating disorders and those who struggle deeply with body image, I hope you can encourage people, especially the ladies, to be at peace with what they've got. "Dream bodies" are often unattainable and acknowledging that such a thing exists (and supporting achievement of that goal, which you do by saying "...this time of year where we really want to slim down, tone up, come into our dream bodies. And we can do that we will do that and it is possible". I appreciate what you say afterwards but it doesn't erase the message (that darn second sentence) that you are sending that says we achieve our dream bodies. Having followed you for some time I know that is likely not the intended message but I had to point it out, as I think a message from you is a powerful one and it is my (literal) job to challenge messages that can be interpreted as harmful from a body image perspective. Again, love you! Just had to address that one.

Acceptance has been huge for me, in so many bad ways as well as good. I've been on a path of recovery for almost 3 years now, however I'm only just over a year sober now. It's been a long road, but the original 30 days of yoga series was there to help me deal with the physical ailments that I could no longer bear in addition to the mental anguish. A year later it is wonderful to see another 30 days of Yoga that has an emphasis on both mental and physical wellness. I'm still a train wreck and I will always struggle with accepting the world as it is, but I accept that the path of recovery doesn't suddenly end and become another path. It is a lifelong adventure and rather than see that as a huge burden I accept that adventure for what it is, challenging and rewarding. Worth it.

Adrienne, this whole last year I've been doing intensive therapy to treat mental illnesses, including pretty severe PTSD and some traits of Borderline Personality Disorder which share the symptoms of disassociation (leaving the body). While it's all helped, I've noticed that I needed a physical departure from the trauma I've experienced because as the more behavioral symptoms have lessened, to a slower extent so have the physiological symptoms. Right around when I started thinking that, I found you and did the original thirty days then found myself transformed. I can tell you're a little hesitant because you're afraid (or you were nervous when you started recording this series) that some YWA people will walk away not understanding the value of what you have to offer with this program. I, however, am so grateful that you're doing this it is EXACTLY what I need right now in my wellness journey and I know I'm not the only one. I accept that today was orientation (I knew you were gonna do that!) so may I offer you you in return a guide for your acceptance. A lot of people will probably stroll,  let them walk. They don't need it right now and may not ever need it -AND- a lot of people will probably find you and then find themselves. What alienates some also unites some and also keeps some where they are. This is the dialectical nature of life we experience in every asana's push-pull-rest. I love you, I trust you, I'm ready. But first, I'mma go do that gentle sequence.
